#|
BIG O - THE CEILING

T(n) = O(f(n)) if and only if T(n)
will eventually bounded above by a constant multipl eof f(n)
it's a permanentceiling that an algorithm running time cannot break above

bound = ceiling that cannot be crossed
bounded above = stays below
T(n) is bounded by f(n) = f(n) acts as 'permanent roof',
no matter what value you put for n, t(n) will never go past that roof

n = input size
n0 = crossover point
T(n) = true time - num of operations your alg takes for input size n
f(n) = benchmark - fun to use as comparison/baseline
O(f(n)) = our function T(n) grows no faster than f(n) once inputs gets large

bounded by a constant multiple of n -> multiply that function by some constant
and check if it will intersect with T(n), if so its true (this is the n0)

c -> constant multiple (vertical scaling/suppress oncstant factor)
n0 -> constant crossover point (large inputs)

T(n) <= c . f(n)
your algorithms steps <= the ceiling
for all n >= n0 (from tis point onward, with no exceptions)

_____

BIG OMEGA - THE FLOOR

T(n) >= c . f(n)
running time cannot drop below

Big O -> absolute worst case
big Omega -> best case baseline (minimum step algorithm is guaranteed to tae)

T(n) = Big Omega(F(n))
once the input n gets large past n0, this algorithm will always
take at least as many steps as our floor (c . f(n))

_____

BIG THETA - THE SANDWICH

_____

LITTLE O -> ceiling that the function can never even get close to (<)



